tside the home. This volume examines the nature of married women’s participation in the economies of three East Asian countries—Japan, Taiwan, and South Korea. In addition to asking what is similar or different about women’s economic participation in this region of the world compared to Western societies, the book also asks how women’s work patterns vary across the three countries. The essays focus on key theoretical questions for the study of women’s labor and, more broadly, economic gender inequality. How do we assess the “value” of work available to married women in different countries and cultural contexts? What forces promote or hinder women’s work outside the home throughout marriage and childrearing? Does wage employment necessarily benefit women more than the “informal” sector (e.g., family-run businesses)? Is full-time work always more desirable than part-time work? Do women who return to the labor force after absences due to family responsibilities incur a heavy wage penalty for interrupted careers? The essays balance comparative assessments in a broad East Asian context with detailed investigations of one or more questions in the context of a specific country. The studies reveal that, although all three countries share common cultural and demographic conditions, patterns of women’s economic participation are distinctly different in Taiwan from those in Japan and South Korea. Whereas women’s participation in Taiwan’s economy shows striking similarities to many Western countries, married women in Japan and Korea participate less in the economy, and their earnings differ more from men’s than in Taiwan or the West. Why is Taiwan more similar to the West while Japan and South Korea are more similar to each other? The book draws on a broad range of materials to explain this puzzle. One of the explanations advanced is that overall labor demand, a greater supply of highly educated men, and more rigid work conditions (especially in large firms) in Japan and South Korea are major obstacles to the equal economic participation of married women in those countries. Also, the greater flexibility in work demands and work hours prevalent in Taiwan is complemented by relatively weaker patriarchal values in the family.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aBrinton, Mary C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrinton, Mary C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHirao, Keiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirata, Shuichi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Sunhwa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Yean-Ju, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Yean-]u, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLu, Yu-Hsia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMehrotra, Nidhi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOgasawara, Yuko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParish, William L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYu, Wei-hsin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478047640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804780476423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804780476/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles